data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code in EF Core 10:

---

## 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your expression-tree manipulation **won't compile**. The parameter is no longer an expression tree, so you can use imperative code directly:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. — conditions go inline.

---

## 2. Complex type column names — now uniquified & nested paths use full path

**Problem A:** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously shared a column silently. EF 10 appends a suffix to disambiguate (e.g., `Street1`). This will generate a migration that renames columns.

**Problem B:** Nested complex types now include the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to column `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of just `BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix** — pin column names explicitly to preserve your existing schema:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City"); // old name
```

---

## 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

All methods (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) now require an additional `string logCommandText` parameter (contains potentially-redacted SQL for logging).

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)  // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

---

**TL;DR:** Delete your expression-tree plumbing (use imperative lambdas), pin complex-type column names with `HasColumnName` to avoid schema drift, and add `string logCommandText` to your diagnostics logger methods.
